  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Small scale business development and community mobilisation for healthy and clean urban slums</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the crowded slums of Malawi&apos;s two major cities, Lilongwe and Blantyre, water has to be stored in people&apos;s homes and easily gets contaminated. Few people have access to toilets, and many of these overflow as there is no emptying system in place. Solid waste is also rarely collected. This project enables local community groups to take on contracts to empty toilets. They also run publicity campaigns to make people more aware of the health risks of contaminated water. Water filters and latrines are sold at low prices, and local people are assisted to start up their own businesses to collect, recycle, and sell waste: the compost is then used for producing flowers and vegetables.</narrative>
  </description>
